nate, Bavaria, Germany":"Pfalz, Bayern, Duitsland","Habsburg, Aargau, Schweiz":"Habsburg, Aargau, Zwitserland","Monte Porzio, Roma, Lazio, Italia":"Monte Porzio Catone, Roma, Lazio, Italië"},"en":{"1110–19 August 1200":"1110–19 August 1200","1110–1200":"1110–1200","1118–Male":"1118–Deceased","1102–1167":"1102–1167","1138–1199":"1138–1199","–Female":"Deceased","1086–1154":"1086–1154","1080–1154":"1080–1154","1080":"1080","19 August 1200":"19 August 1200","1110":"1110","1154":"1154","19. August 1167":"19 August 1167","1086":"1086","1118":"1118","1138":"1138","25. November 1199":"25 November 1199","nach 1154":"after 1154","1102":"1102","1167":"1167","1200":"1200","1199":"1199","Homburg, Palatinate, Bavaria, Germany":"Palatinate, Bavaria, Germany","Habsburg, Aargau, Schweiz":"Habsburg, Aargau, Switzerland","Monte Porzio, Roma, Lazio, Italia":"Monte Porzio Catone, Roma, Lazio, Italy","nameMeanings":[{"name":"von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Homberg","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Fritz.  Jewish Aron.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic):","habitational name from any of various places in Germany so called. The placename is derived from an inflected form of Old High German <i>hōh</i> ‘high’ + <i>berg</i> ‘mountain, hill’."],"variants":[{"name":"Homberger","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Homberg (see   Homberg   1)."]},{"name":"Homburg","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Dieter, Hans, Otto.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from any of the places in Hesse and Saarland called Homburg, from the weak dative case (originally used after a preposition and article) of Old High German <i>hōh</i> ‘high’ + <i>burg</i> ‘fortress, fortified town’."]},{"name":"Gomberg","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Mandel.  Russian Aleksandr, Arkadiy, Boris, Galina, Grigory, Iosif, Mordko, Vitaly, Vladimir, Yevgeniy, Yevgeniya, Yulia.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of   Homberg  . The initial <i>g</i> is due to Russian influence, since Russian has no <i>h</i> and alters it to <i>g</i> in borrowed words and names."]}]},{"name":"Ida","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Norman name, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>īd</i> ‘work’. This died out during the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, influenced by its use in  Tennyson's  The Princess (  1847 ) for the central character, who devotes herself to the cause of women's rights and women's education in a thoroughly Victorian way. The name is also associated with Mount Ida in Crete, which was connected in classical times with the worship of Zeus, king of the gods, who was supposed to have been brought up in a cave on the mountainside. In the 1930s it became famous as the name of the film star  Ida Lupino  (  1914–1995 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ida von Homberg was born in 1110, in Palatinate, Bavaria, Germany, her father, Graf Werner von Homberg-Tierstein, was 25 and her mother, N.N. von Zollern, was 30. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Werner II. Graf von Habsburg. She died on 19 August 1200, at the age of 90."},"et":{"1110–19 August 1200":"1110–19. august 1200","1110–1200":"1110–1200","1118–Male":"1118–Surnud","1102–1167":"1102–1167","1138–1199":"1138–1199","–Female":"Surnud","